<DOC><DOCNO> AP880505-0135 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 1233EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-US-Hostages     05-05 0141</FIRST><SECOND>PM-US-Hostages,140</SECOND><HEAD>Administration Hopes No Deals Were Made for French Hostages</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Reagan administration said today it stilldoes not believe in deals with hostage-takers and hopes none wasmade for the freedom of the three French hostages released inLebanon.   ``We hope that deals were not made of a kind that we object toin our own policies on terrorism,'' White House spokesman MarlinFitzwater said. ``We always hold the kidnappers responsible for thesafety of the hostages and we certainly hold them responsible forthe remaining hostages there.''   ``We do not have details on the negotiations or what happened inthis case, but nevertheless our policy is unchanged,'' Fitzwatersaid. ``We do not believe we should make deals withhostage-takers.''   Nine Americans, three Britons and six others are still believedto be captive in Lebanon.</TEXT></DOC>